{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521498"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:35:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:35:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13687"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13687","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13687"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.58,0.17,0.05,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6295"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108358"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6295","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6295"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13687"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90748"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2267"},{"type":"tags","id":"2702"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11651"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43430"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44738"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108358","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108358"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with an eight-month history of progressive exertional dyspnoea and dry cough. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He works as a stonemason and has been cutting and installing engineered stone benchtops for the past 12 years. He lives on a farm with exposure to hay and birds. He had a summer job in construction during university with brief exposure to asbestos.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 72/min, blood pressure 128/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Chest auscultation reveals fine inspiratory crackles in the upper zones bilaterally. A chest X-ray shows small nodular opacities in the upper lobes with hilar lymphadenopathy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Asbestosis","Silicosis","Sarcoidosis","Idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis","Hypersensitivity pneumonitis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s 12-year history of cutting and installing engineered stone benchtops, combined with upper lobe nodular opacities and hilar lymphadenopathy on chest X-ray, strongly suggests \u003Cstrong\u003Esilicosis\u003C/strong\u003E. Engineered stone can contain over 90% crystalline silica, and inhalation of respirable silica dust during cutting and polishing causes inflammation and fibrosis in the lungs. The radiographic pattern of upper lobe predominant nodules with hilar lymphadenopathy is characteristic of silicosis. Australia has recently banned engineered stone benchtops due to the high incidence of severe early-onset silicosis in exposed workers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAsbestosis\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely given the patient\u0027s limited asbestos exposure during a single summer job. Asbestosis requires significant cumulative exposure and typically presents with lower lobe predominant fibrosis rather than upper lobe nodules. While mesothelioma can occur with minimal asbestos exposure, asbestosis cannot.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESarcoidosis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with similar radiographic findings of upper lobe nodules and hilar lymphadenopathy. However, it is not associated with occupational exposures and often presents with extrapulmonary manifestations such as skin lesions, uveitis, or hypercalcaemia, which are absent in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIdiopathic pulmonary fibrosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects older patients and presents with basilar predominant subpleural reticulation and honeycombing on imaging, not upper lobe nodules. It is a diagnosis of exclusion when no clear cause for interstitial lung disease is identified.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypersensitivity pneumonitis\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered given the patient\u0027s exposure to hay and birds on his farm. However, the radiological pattern of upper lobe nodules with lymphadenopathy, combined with significant occupational silica exposure, makes silicosis far more likely than hypersensitivity pneumonitis, which typically shows diffuse ground-glass opacities or centrilobular nodules.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Silicosis is an occupational lung disease caused by inhalation of crystalline silica dust, particularly in workers cutting engineered stone benchtops containing over 90% silica.","Silicosis typically presents with upper lobe nodular opacities and hilar lymphadenopathy on chest X-ray.","Engineered stone benchtops have been banned in Australia due to the high incidence of severe early-onset silicosis in exposed workers."],"references":["Baum L, Arnold TC. Silicosis. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2024 [cited 2024 Jun 26]. Available at: http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK594245/","Nemec SF, Bankier AA, Eisenberg RL. Upper lobe-predominant diseases of the lung. AJR Am J Roentgenol. 2013 Mar;200(3):W222-37. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23436867/","Kirby T. Australia bans engineered stone to prevent silicosis. The Lancet Respiratory Medicine. 2024;12(4):e18. Available at: https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lanres/article/PIIS2213-2600(24)00007-9/abstract","Li T, Yang X, Xu H, Liu H. Early Identification, Accurate Diagnosis, and Treatment of Silicosis. Can Respir J. 2022;2022:3769134. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9061058/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90748"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13687"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90748","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90748"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-09T18:40:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-09T18:40:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6295"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108358"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCoun